|><| 𝐢𝐟-𝐞𝐥𝐬𝐞 𝐬𝐭𝐚𝐭𝐞𝐦𝐞𝐧𝐭 |><|
       >> if-statement is used to test a condition. It checks boolean condition.
       >> true or false

   Syntax ::--
     if (condition) {
         // Code to execute if the condition is true
      } else {
       // Code to execute if the condition is false
      }

 𝙵𝚘𝚛 𝙴𝚡𝚊𝚖𝚙𝚕𝚎 ::--
  class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int number = 10;

        if (number > 15) {
            System.out.println("True");
        } else {
            System.out.println("False");
               }
          }
       }

    >> The if statement executes the block of code if the condition evaluates to true.
    >> The else block is optional and is executed when the condition evaluates to false.

---------------------><--------------------><---------------------

|><| 𝐒𝐰𝐢𝐭𝐜𝐡 𝐒𝐭𝐚𝐭𝐞𝐦𝐞𝐧𝐭 |><|
       >> A switch statement in Java is used for decision-making based on the value of a variable or an expression. 
       >> It allows you to execute one block of code out of multiple options, based on the matching case.

1. 𝙵𝚘𝚛 𝙴𝚡𝚊𝚖𝚙𝚕𝚎 ::-- Basic Switch

  class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int day = 3;

        switch (day) {
            case 1:
                System.out.println("Monday");
                break;
            case 2:
                System.out.println("Tuesday");
                break;
            case 3:
                System.out.println("Wednesday");
                break;
            case 4:
                System.out.println("Thursday");
                break;
            case 5:
                System.out.println("Friday");
                break;
            default:
                System.out.println("Weekend");
        }
    }
}

2. 𝙵𝚘𝚛 𝙴𝚡𝚊𝚖𝚙𝚕𝚎 ::-- String Switch

 class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String color = "Red";

        switch (color) {
            case "Red":
                System.out.println("You chose Red.");
                break;
            case "Green":
                System.out.println("You chose Green.");
                break;
            case "Blue":
                System.out.println("You chose Blue.");
                break;
            default:
                System.out.println("Color not recognized.");
        }
    }
}

3. 𝙵𝚘𝚛 𝙴𝚡𝚊𝚖𝚙𝚕𝚎 ::-- Switch Without Break (Fallthrough)

 class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int number = 2;

        switch (number) {
            case 1:
                System.out.println("Case 1");
            case 2:
                System.out.println("Case 2");
            case 3:
                System.out.println("Case 3");
            default:
                System.out.println("Default case");
        }
    }
}

